{{ill|Tochigi Gokoku Shrine|ja|栃木県護国神社|1=Tochigi Gokoku Shrine|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tochigi Gokoku Shrine|13=User:Immanuelle/Tochigi Gokoku Shrine|qq=}} is a {{ill|Shinto shrine|en|Shinto shrine|WD=Q845945|lt=Shinto shrine|1=Shinto shrine}} located in {{ill|Japan|en|Japan|WD=Q17|lt=Japan|1=Japan}}.  It is a [[Gokoku Shrines|Gokoku Shrine]], or a shrine dedicated to war dead.{{Efn|Is this [[WP:BLUE]] considering that the shrine is literally named as such?}} Such shrines were made to serve to enshrine the war dead, and they were all considered "branches" of {{ill|Yasukuni Shrine|en|Yasukuni Shrine|WD=Q242803|lt=Yasukuni Shrine|1=Yasukuni Shrine}}. They were renamed from {{ill|Shōkonsha|en|Shōkonsha|WD=Q11497810|lt=Shokonsha|1=Shōkonsha}} in 1939.<ref>{{Cite journal |last=TAKAYAMA |first=K. PETER |date=1990 |title=Enshrinement and Persistency of Japanese Religion |url=https://www.jstor.org/stable/23917081 |journal=Journal of Church and State |volume=32 |issue=3 |pages=527–547 |issn=0021-969X}}</ref>

In 1996 before a visit the {{ill|Imperial Household Agency|en|Imperial Household Agency|WD=Q1143602|lt=Imperial Household Agency|1=Imperial Household Agency}} inquired about potential war criminals at the shrine. <ref>{{Citation |title=Yasukuni Fundamentalism |date=2021-07-31 |url=http://dx.doi.org/10.2307/j.ctv1jpf1pk.11 |work= |pages=207 |access-date=2023-10-25 |publisher=University of Hawaii Press}}</ref>

'''Tochigi Prefecture Gokoku Shrine''' ({{nihongo|栃木県護国神社|1=Tochigi Gokoku Shrine|Tochigi-ken Gokoku Jinja}}) is a {{ill|Shinto shrine|en|Shinto shrine|WD=Q845945|lt=Shinto shrine|1=Shinto shrine}} ({{ill|Gokoku shrines|en|Gokoku shrines|WD=Q1534477|lt=Gokoku shrine|1=Gokoku Shrines}}) located in {{ill|Utsunomiya|en|Utsunomiya|WD=Q200589|lt=Utsunomiya, Tochigi|1=Utsunomiya}}, Tochigi Prefecture, Japan. It honors spirits from Tochigi Prefecture who died in wars such as the {{ill|Boshin War|en|Boshin War|WD=Q309184|lt=Boshin War|1=Boshin War}}, {{ill|First Sino-Japanese War|en|First Sino-Japanese War|WD=Q178687|lt=First Sino-Japanese War|1=First Sino-Japanese War}}, {{ill|Russo-Japanese War|en|Russo-Japanese War|WD=Q159950|lt=Russo-Japanese War|1=Russo-Japanese War}}, and {{ill|Pacific War|en|Pacific War|WD=Q184425|lt=Pacific War|1=Pacific War}} as well as deceased police officers, firefighters, and members of the {{ill|Japan Self-Defense Forces|en|Japan Self-Defense Forces|WD=Q275488|lt=Japan Self-Defense Forces|1=Japan Self-Defense Forces}}.

== History ==
The shrine traces its origins to 1872 (Meiji 5) when 97 spirits from the Boshin War, including those of Lord {{ill|Toda Tadayuki|lt=Toda Tadayuki|lt=Tadaaki Toda|ja|戸田忠恕|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tadaaki Toda|qq=}}, the former [[daimyo]] of Utsunomiya, and his retainers, were enshrined in Utsunomiya's Baba Town at the site of the original {{nihongo|Utsunomiya Shōkonsha|宇都宮招魂社}}.<ref name="#1">栃木県神社誌, p. 221</ref>

In 1939 (Showa 14), the shrine was designated a {{ill|Home Ministry|en|Home Ministry|WD=Q1142265|lt=Home Ministry|1=Home Ministry}}-approved Gokoku Shrine and renamed Tochigi Prefecture Gokoku Shrine. It was relocated to its current site in 1940 (Showa 15). After the war, it was briefly renamed {{nihongo|Shōtoku Shrine|彰徳神社}} in 1947, but reverted to its former name in 1953 following the withdrawal of occupation forces.<ref name="#1"/>

On July 25, 1996 (Heisei 8), Emperor {{nihongo|Akihito|上皇明仁}} and Empress {{nihongo|Michiko|上皇后美智子}} officially visited and paid their respects at the shrine. The event marked the first instance of a Gokoku Shrine being officially visited by the Emperor and Empress.

In 2010 (Heisei 22), a prominent Japanese evergreen oak tree within the shrine grounds was transplanted to make way for road expansion, demonstrating efforts to preserve the area's heritage.<ref name="shimotsuke1">{{cite news|title=見守られて引っ越し 護国神社のシイの木 地域のシンボルへ期待|newspaper=[[下野新聞]]|date=2010-03-19}}</ref>

The shrine also hosts memorials, including a monument dedicated in 2010 to young men who perished in {{ill|Kamikaze|en|Kamikaze|WD=Q133194|lt=Kamikaze|1=Kamikaze}} missions during the {{ill|Pacific War|en|Pacific War|WD=Q184425|lt=Pacific War|1=Pacific War}}.<ref name="shimotsuke3">{{cite news|title=とちぎ戦後65th year  節目に「[[特攻勇士の像]]」 元将校ら「語り継ぎたい」 宇都宮の護国神社 あす除幕式|newspaper=下野新聞|date=2010-08-14}}</ref>

== Annual Events ==
* '''New Year's Festival''' (January 1)
* '''First Shrine Visit''' (January 1–31)
* '''Kinen-sai''' (February 17)
* '''Reitaisai''' (April 28)
* '''War Memorial Peace Festival''' (August 15)
* '''Shichi-Go-San Festival''' (November 15)
* '''Niiname-sai''' (November 23)

== Notable Features ==
The shrine grounds include a model of a {{ill|Mitsubishi_A6M_Zero|en|Mitsubishi_A6M_Zero|WD=Q40156|lt=Mitsubishi A6M Zero|1=Mitsubishi A6M Zero}} fighter plane, donated by famed composer {{ill|Toru Funamura|ja|船村徹|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Toru Funamura|qq=}}, displayed near the main hall.
